<p>WhatsApp says Russia tried to “fully block” the messaging service—an effort the company sees as pushing people toward a state-backed alternative as the government tightens control over online communications. For everyday users, the immediate impact is uncertainty. Even short disruptions can make it harder to keep up with family, communities, and business contacts—and can add pressure to move to domestic platforms.</p><h3>Highlights:</h3><ul><li>Why it matters in Russia: WhatsApp is reported to have roughly 90 million to about 100 million users in the country, so any disruption would hit everyday communication at scale.</li><li>Name of the state-backed rival: Coverage links the disruption to promotion of a state-backed “national messenger,” and one report identifies it as Max.</li><li>Not the first restriction: The move follows earlier limits on calls from messaging apps, including WhatsApp and Telegram, reported in 2025—suggesting a tightening trend rather than a one-off.</li><li>WhatsApp pushes back: A WhatsApp spokesperson called the move a “backwards step,” underscoring the company’s opposition to the restrictions.</li></ul><h3>Perspectives:</h3><ul><li>WhatsApp (Meta-owned): WhatsApp frames the restrictions as an attempt to steer users toward a state-backed messenger it calls a “state-owned surveillance app.” (<a href='https://www.bbc.com/news/articles/clygd10pg5lo'>BBC News</a>)</li><li>Kremlin/Russian authorities: Russian officials say WhatsApp can keep operating in Russia only if it complies with Russian law, casting enforcement as a compliance issue. (<a href='https://www.dw.com/en/russia-moves-to-block-whatsapp-as-moscow-pushes-state-backed-rival/a-75922756'>Deutsche Welle</a>)</li><li>Coverage of the state alternative: Reports say Moscow is encouraging use of a more tightly controlled domestic service and a state-backed “national messenger,” linking the WhatsApp disruption to a broader push for home-grown platforms. (<a href='https://www.thehindu.com/sci-tech/technology/whatsapp-says-russia-attempted-to-fully-block-app/article70622851.ece'>The Hindu</a>)</li></ul><h3>Sources:</h3><ul><li><a href='https://www.thehindu.com/sci-tech/technology/whatsapp-says-russia-attempted-to-fully-block-app/article70622851.ece'>WhatsApp says Russia &#x27;attempted to fully block&#x27; app</a> - thehindu.com</li><li><a href='https://www.straitstimes.com/world/europe/whatsapp-says-russia-tried-to-fully-block-service-to-push-state-app'>WhatsApp says Russia tried to fully block service to push state app</a> - straitstimes.com</li><li><a href='https://www.bbc.com/news/articles/clygd10pg5lo'>Russia moves to block WhatsApp in messaging app crackdown</a> - bbc.com</li><li><a href='https://www.dw.com/en/russia-moves-to-block-whatsapp-as-moscow-pushes-state-backed-rival/a-75922756'>Russia moves to block WhatsApp as Moscow pushes state-backed rival</a> - dw.com</li><li><a href='https://www.ndtv.com/world-news/russia-blocks-metas-whatsapp-messaging-service-ft-reports-10991552#publisher=newsstand'>WhatsApp, With 100 Million Users In Russia, Claims Moscow Tried To Block It</a> - ndtv.com</li><li><a href='https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/feb/12/russia-attempt-block-whatsapp-meta-says'>Russia attempted to ‘fully block’ WhatsApp, Meta-owned company says</a> - theguardian.com</li></ul>